[1] USA: Texas nurse recovered
Date: Fri 24 Oct 2014
Source: Washington Post [edited]
http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dallas-nurse-treated-for-ebola-at-nih-now-virus-free/2014/10/24/91355cd2-5b8c-11e4-bd61-346aee66ba29_story.html


Nina Pham, nurse who contracted Ebola, is now free of virus and leaves NIH
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Nina Pham, the 1st nurse diagnosed with Ebola in the United States, walked out of the National Institutes of Health on Friday morning [24 Oct 2014] after doctors there declared her free of the Ebola virus. Pham, 26, had cared for an infected Ebola patient in Dallas [Texas]. She was treated at the Bethesda, Maryland, USA facility, which has a special unit for patients who need advanced isolation and extended stays. "She has no virus in her," said Anthony S Fauci, director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, at a news conference. "She feels well." He said Pham "looks extraordinarily well." He described her as an "extraordinarily courageous and lovely person" and a "devoted nurse." ...

Pham later in the day met with President Obama at the White House. At his daily press briefing White House press secretary Josh Earnest said the president's decision to greet Pham was "an opportunity, 1st of all, to thank her for her service." Pham did not undergo any additional medical testing before greeting -- and hugging -- the president, Earnest said, noting that she had been shown to be free of the virus on 5 separate occasions before being released.

At the news conference in Bethesda, Pham said she is looking forward to returning to Texas and to a normal life with her dog, Bentley. Her King Charles spaniel was quarantined after Pham was diagnosed. He tested negative for Ebola but is still in his 21-day incubation period until the end of the month [October 2014], according to Texas officials.... -- more

[byline: Dan Morse]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Evidence of infection of dogs with an ebolavirus in Africa was reported in ProMED-mail post Ebolavirus, animal reservoir (04): canine, control, comment 20141024.2895085. I do not know of any report of Ebola symptoms in dogs, and there are no reports of suspicious dog deaths in the 3 countries.

"To ultimately 'prove' that an animal is carrying a productive infection would be very difficult in a heavily contaminated environment. PCR, because of its sensitivity, could easily yield a false positive under these circumstances. So might virus isolation, unless proper procedures were strictly adhered to. Immunohistochemistry of target tissues might be considered, if specific reagents are available. Always, we need to be aware of the severe risks associated with detailed investigation of Ebola virus disease." (See Cor Lenghaus, BVSc (Hons) PhD, Australia <corlenghaus@bigpond.com> in the ProMED post referenced above).

It is interesting that as far as incubation period is concerned, authorities are treating the dog as a human -- without any experimental evidence to support that. It would be helpful if such evidence could be obtained. - Mod.JW]

